Located behind the temporary gate that led into the temple, this shrub had managed to find a well-hidden and partially shaded niche in the cracks of the pavement that led to the temple. This specimen was around the height of 1.5 liter soft-drink bottle during my visit.

This sacred fig sapling had found its way into a rock cranny in one of the many pavements outside of Ang Mo Kio Secondary School. This specimen appears to be a weed in many parts of Singapore that I have visited, given its relative ubiquity and ability to tolerate small spaces. This may be in part due to its aesthetic beauty and the relative un-intrusive nature of its root networks, hence relegating it to the bottom of a weed-remover's prerogatives when extermination of unwanted plants are concerned.
